         <abstract>
            <p>With the support of the Undergraduate Instructional Awards Program of the University of Illinois, an attempt was made to teach introductory sociology using selections from fifteen novels and one play as supplementary reading material. The evaluation of this innovation conducted by the Office of Instructional Resources of the University resulted in several conclusions: (1) students taught through these materials indicate that it is a good method; (2) students feel that such materials substantially improve their understanding of sociological concepts; (3) in the absence of a comparative study using control groups, it is difficult to assess whether students do learn more through this method, although some tentative suggestions concerning its unique value are made; and (4) serious obstacles exist to the successful utilization of these materials, related to both the instructor(s) and the materials themselves, and recommendations for overcoming these obstacles are proposed.</p>
          </abstract>
